manufacturerProductDescription.media_text: Charming with layering effect C175 USB drive uses matte finish and glossy finish to create a sleek uniqueness. The difference between the two textures can enhance the visual layering effect and makes the C175 USB drive looks dazzling with a unique attractiveness.

Another option: TEAMGROUP C175 ECO C175 ECO Net-Zero USB is made with 75% post-consumer recycled material, contributing to sustainability endeavors. 128GB-512GB C175 ECO- Concealed click keep the cap from losing C175 ECO USB features a concealed click fastener design to store the cap, preventing loss wherever and whenever. Loss reduction also contributes to Earth conservation. Learn More

Plug and play interface C175 USB drive is using USB 3.2 Gen 1 (3.0/3.1) interface. Capacities are available from smallest 16GB to largest 128GB, which can satisfy consumers' need for high-speed transfer and multimedia file storage, the plug and play interface also makes file sharing easier than ever before.

Ingenious seamless design The seamless design of the entire USB body is different from other products in the market; it does not scratch your hands or collect dust and get dirty easily. The well-proportioned, rounded appearance and the ingenious seamless design make it look simple, sleek and elegant. Avoid cap loss with a unique design After thoughtfully considering the behavior of consumers, a hidden latch is added to the design of the C175 USB drive. When using the USB drive, plug the cap to the back to avoid the cap loss problem. Besides the convenience, the elegant and aesthetic overall design can also be maintained.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 24, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Writing is a bit slow, but NTFS reformatting works & plays nicely w/ USB hub
reviews.reviewText: [EDIT: changed 'word' to 'works' in title]Of course there's only 116GB not 128 (but you knew that). Reformatting to NTFS worked fine for me. After using them for about six months I haven't seen any data loss issues. At the price, they're a good buy. Writing is not particularly fast as noted in the review headline. (Also if you have a laptop you can get four of these on a USB hub - effectively extending your storage space by a bit less than 1/2 TB.) I've even tried "daisy chaining" a hub and that seems to work okay provided you aren't accessing more than one at a time.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 8, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 4.0 out of 5 stars Buyer beware, this drive is as slow as many other "USB 3.0" drives (5MBps) [Updated]
reviews.reviewText: This is one of the first affordable 512GB USB flash drives I've seen, so I purchased 2 of them.Unfortunately, they are just as slow as the other USB flash drives I've bought from PNY, Sandisk, and Micro Center. Write speeds began when writing 168GB of data at about 100 megabytes per second, but quickly dropped to 5 megabytes per second which is what I've come to expect from basically every brand except for Samsung. The reason the write speed appears high at the start is due to it writing to a local cache on the drive (usually comprised of RAM or an SLC cache) and it drops to the true write speed once that cache is exhausted. The other thing to keep in mind is that you cannot disconnect the drive till this write cache is written to the storage otherwise you will lose all of that data as the write cache is volatile. So users that may not want to write as much will be stuck waiting for it to write at the abysmally low 5MBps write speed if they want to keep their files they just tried to write to the disk.It's truly a shame Teamgroup can't produce a drive with a better sustained write speed and I expected better from them after buying their SSDs for all of my computer builds. Very disappointed. Only good for an archive drive. Stick to their SSDs and buy a Samsung flash drive like the fit or the bar if you want it to be truly fast.[Update] I underwent more testing and figured out that these drives do not work well with NTFS and handle small files worse than my BAR drives. They noticeable worked far better with exFAT as the filesystem in my experience. The difference was major and immediate since switching over. I think the issue either comes down to the controller or the flash used. Regardless, take note it does function well, but only when using FAT or FAT based systems (FAT32/exFAT). Shame because NTFS is far more reliable in terms of recoverability so 4/5.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 9, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Good value drives
reviews.reviewText: Price and performance keep improving - I never thought I'd see anything with specs like this in a USB thumb drive -I got 3-pack of the 64gb and it does exceed the 100MB/s advertised read speeds - coming in at 130MB/s on the sequential read tests. But ONLY for reading - and you really won't get this kind of speed in real-world use anytime anywhere.The more disappointing reality is that the random read and random write speeds are both pretty horrible at (on my Crystal result) a little less than 4MB/s on read and around 1.5MB/s on random writes. Even the sequential writes take substantial hit from reads with the writes coming in at 38MB/s.Still, for this price and capacity, it fills a need. I've had good experience with Teamgroup products.*****
